The core concept

For art use, every species file should not just say “what it is.” It should say:
	•	what stage is visually iconic
	•	what shape language it uses
	•	what surface/finish it gives you
	•	what color range it tends to hit
	•	what substrates it appears on
	•	what scale fantasy it suggests
	•	what it can be remixed into: jewelry, architecture, alien flesh, lace, coral, circuitry, fungal couture, etc.

Because the real visual gold is in the lifecycle. Plasmodial slime molds pass through spores → amoeboid/swarm cells → zygote → multinucleate plasmodium → fruiting bodies, and can also form hardened resting stages like sclerotia. Cellular slime molds do the “lonely amoebae become a coordinated slug and then a fruiting body” thing, and many also have cyst cycles or sexual macrocysts. Protostelids make tiny simple sporocarps on stalks.  ￼

The lifecycle files you absolutely want

This part matters a lot. Don’t skip it.

1. Plasmodial lifecycle

This is your big dramatic monster file:
	•	spores
	•	myxamoebae
	•	flagellated swarm cells
	•	cell fusion
	•	zygote
	•	young plasmodium
	•	mature vein-network plasmodium
	•	fan-shaped feeding fronts
	•	sclerotium
	•	primordia
	•	fruiting initiation
	•	sporangia / aethalia / pseudoaethalia / plasmodiocarps
	•	capillitium and spore release

These are the famous “yellow web on bark / foamy blob / coral candelabra / metallic bead towers” bastards.  ￼

2. Cellular lifecycle

For dictyostelids:
	•	solitary amoebae
	•	starvation signal / aggregation centers
	•	streaming cell rivers
	•	mound
	•	migrating slug / grex
	•	culmination
	•	sorocarp (stalk + spore mass)
	•	microcyst
	•	macrocyst

This is the social choreography one. Tiny, but conceptually sexy as hell.  ￼

3. Protostelid lifecycle
	•	amoeboid feeding cell
	•	tiny sporocarp initiation
	•	simple stalk
	•	one/few spores
	•	collapse / dispersal

These are minimalist little perverts. Great for micro-ornament logic.  ￼

